ile still handling complex gating logic.\n\nNow I'm sketching out the implementation structure. I'll create a few focused files: types for all the interfaces, the main TaskQueue class to handle everything, a simple cron parser, and an index for re-exports. Let me start building out the types and core class...\n\nDefining the types and TaskQueue class... I'm settling on making Task a class to encapsulate behavior, and now I have a clear picture of the implementation.\n\nFor the cron parser, I need to handle basic patterns like every N minutes, hourly, and daily schedules by parsing the minute and hour fields. The middleware pipeline will use a chain pattern where each middleware receives the task and a next function, then the registered processing handler gets invoked after the middleware chain completes. I'm trying to recall how take() worked in the earlier phases to understand the full flow. returns the task and the caller decides what to do with it. How does middleware fit in?\n\nI think the flow is:\n- `tq.process(queueName, handler)` registers a handler\n- When `tq.take(queueName)` is called, it runs the task through middleware before returning\n- Or maybe `process` is a higher-level API that calls take internally?\n\nActually, let me re-read phase 11 requirements more carefully... The explore agent said:\n- Per-queue middleware functions\n- Task passes through middleware stack in order\n- Middleware receives task and \"next\" function\n- Middleware can modify task, skip, or fail\n- Processing handler invoked after middleware\n- Each queue has independent middleware stack\n- Middleware errors mark task as failed\n\nSo the middleware runs when a task is about to be processed, and I'm trying to figure out whether `process()` should be the entry point that handles middleware, or if middleware should be applied during `take()`. Looking at how Bull and similar systems work, `process()` typically registers a handler and the queue automatically processes tasks, but for